Chris,<br><br>
Thanks for your ideas on anger. Anger is one of those backdoor PTSD things. I am now in the middle of a class on anger management. Your perception on my anger is really good, and many of the issues you raise I am now addressing! Yes, I have a lot of anger on issues about the Vietnam War, but this is not the right forum for me to let it all hang out right now. I have other outlets that keep my head on straight while I am in the process of sorting it all out. <br>
Sometimes, it breaks through here a little, but that's OK, too. PTSD people can be people of extremes at times, and I need to work my reasoned middle ground here to make sure I stay in touch with myself. As far as Doc Spatz is concerned, <br>
check out my latest posts to him here and up on site 44. If you look around the corner, you will see anger there too!<br><br>
JJ,<br><br>
I will track down the PTSD article. It is ironic that what I now see in myself is somewhat parallel to what I now recollect about my Father who was in the pacific in WW2 as a tail gunner. His mind really went south when he was in the early 40's. There was no net out there to catch him, though.<br><br>

